"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767377","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>In line with the Scottish Parliament’s legislative competence, the promotion and construction of railways that start, end and remain in Scotland is a matter for the Scottish Government. We look to the relevant local authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) in the Transport for the North partnership, in developing a comprehensive transport strategy for the North of England, to decide whether to engage with the Scottish Government and other stakeholders on the commissioning of such assessments.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-10-17T12:46:09.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767377/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767377/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Borders Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with the Scottish Government about re-opening the rest of the Waverley route from Edinburgh to Carlisle following the partial opening to Tweedbank.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767378","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-19","<p>Natural England has set up a regulators’ group involving officials from the Scottish Government, Scottish Natural Heritage, Defra, the Forestry Commission and the Animal and Plant Health Agency. The group has met and discussed the application and will continue to liaise regularly.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-10-19T12:22:28.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767378/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767378/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Kielder Forest: Lynx","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussion they have had with the Scottish Government about the proposed release of lynx animals in Kielder Forest which straddles the border between England and Scotland.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767379","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>While we have not made specific representations to the Israeli authorities over this issue, we have regularly raised our concerns with the Israeli authorities about the Israel Defense Forces' use of live fire, urging robust and transparent investigations where appropriate.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-19T11:12:33.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767379/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767379/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Raed al-Salhi","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the death of Raed al-Salhi after a raid by Israeli soldiers on his home.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767380","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government remains gravely concerned about continued demolition of Palestinian property by the Israeli authorities including proposals to demolish the Bedouin villages of Khan al-Ahmar and Susiya. The Minister for the Middle East and North Africa visited Susiya in August 2017.</p><p>The UK has repeatedly called on the Israeli authorities to halt proposals to demolish Khan al-Ahmar. Prior to the most recently scheduled Israeli High Court hearing on the matter on 25 September – subsequently postponed - our Embassy in Tel Aviv raised our concerns with the Israeli authorities on 24 September. The Foreign Secretary expressed our concern about the proposals when he met Prime Minister Netanyahu in Israel on 8 March.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-19T11:12:14.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767380/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767380/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Israel: Bedouin","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the planned demolition of the Palestinian communities of Susiya and Khan Al Ahmar.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767381","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>While we have not raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, we remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of movement. Through our Embassy in Tel Aviv we have lobbied the appropriate authorities on the issue of movement and access. We continue to work closely with the Quartet and EU partners to call on Israel to ease restrictions on access.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-19T11:11:34.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767381/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767381/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they made to the government of Israel following its decision to seal off the West Bank and Gaza Strip from 4 to 14 October over the Jewish holiday of Sukkot.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767382","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>While we have not raised this specific issue, we have consistently called on the Israeli Government to ease movement and access restrictions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories. We are supporting the UN Access Coordination Unit who work with the World Health Organisation, Israeli Government, Palestinian Authority (PA) and aid agencies to facilitate the transfer of medical equipment and supplies, as well as patient referrals in and out of Gaza. We are aware that Israeli hospitals do treat Palestinian patients following referrals from the PA.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-23T15:59:48.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767382/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767382/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Israel: Gaza","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they made to the government of Israel following the report from Medical Aid for Palestinians that five female cancer patients died in August after being prevented from attending hospital appointments outside Gaza.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767383","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>We regularly raise with the Israeli Government the need for proportionality to any protest and accountability for security incidents, plus full access to justice for any victims.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-23T14:22:09.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767383/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767383/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel in response to reports that Israeli forces are using live ammunition on Palestinians during confrontation and military raids.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767384","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>​We have not had any recent contact with the Government of Israel on this issue. However, we will seek to raise concerns over the respect for places of worship with the appropriate Israeli authorities in the near future.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-23T14:24:21.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767384/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767384/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Israel: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding the more than 53 mosques and churches that have been vandalised in Israel and the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767391","Attorney General","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not maintain a central record of the number of prosecutions or convictions for abusive behaviour on social media platforms. This information could only be obtained by examining CPS case files, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-10-17T16:03:59.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767391/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767391/answer",,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-10-09","Social Media: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many prosecutions there were for abusive behaviour on social media platforms in each of the last three years; and how many of those prosecutions resulted in a conviction.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767392","Attorney General","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) maintains a central record of the number of defendants flagged as involving domestic abuse that were prosecuted and convicted through its Case Management System.</p><p>The table below shows the volume and proportion of domestic abuse prosecutions and convictions during each of the last three years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2014 - 15</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2015 - 16</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2016 - 17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Volume</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Volume</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Volume</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Convictions</p></td><td><p>68,601</p></td><td><p>73.9%</p></td><td><p>75,235</p></td><td><p>74.5%</p></td><td><p>70,853</p></td><td><p>75.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Unsuccessful</p></td><td><p>24,178</p></td><td><p>26.1%</p></td><td><p>25,695</p></td><td><p>25.5%</p></td><td><p>22,737</p></td><td><p>24.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>92,779</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>100,930</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>93,590</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Data Source: CPS Case Management Information System</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-10-18T10:08:02.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767392/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767392/answer",,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-10-09","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many prosecutions for violence in a domestic setting there were in each of the last three years; and how many of those prosecutions resulted in a conviction.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767393","Home Office","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Office for National Statistics publishes information on the number of incidents of domestic abuse recorded by the police. This information is published in a cross government statistical bulletin ‘Domestic abuse in England and Wales: year ending March 2016’, which can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/bulletins/domesticabuseinenglandandwales/yearendingmarch2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/bulletins/domesticabuseinenglandandwales/yearendingmarch2016</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-20T09:30:03.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767393/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767393/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-09","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents of domestic violence were reported to police authorities in England and Wales in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767394","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Parliamentary Secretary at the Cabinet Office notified Parliament of the forecast cost<br>of the UK general election of £140,850,000 in a Written Ministerial Statement on 13<br>September 2017 (Hansard Volume 628, reference HCWS130).</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-19T11:07:37.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767394/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767394/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-09","General Election 2017: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what was the cost to the public purse of holding the general election 2017.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","106643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767395","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>This information is not held by the Cabinet Office.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T14:40:27.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767395/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767395/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-09","Government Departments: Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the average broadband download speed is across the Government estate (a) in and (b) outside London.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767396","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>EU Exit is an all-of- government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p>Members of staff across the Department may at times be required to provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. But given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-24T16:02:04.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767396/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767396/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-09","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767397","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-17","<p>The government has taken significant steps to tackle the promoters of tax avoidance schemes. It introduced the Promoters of Tax Avoidance Schemes (POTAS) regime in Budget 2013 to tackle high-risk promoters, and Finance Bill 2017-2019 goes further by introducing a new penalty on the enablers of tax avoidance.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-17T11:27:43.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767397/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767397/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans the Government has to introduce legislation to restrict promoters of tax avoidance schemes.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","106451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767398","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government Property Unit is responsible for minimising vacancy by supporting departments to sell, sublet, find alternative use, and to do early surrenders. Interventions such as these have contributed significantly to minimising the vacancy rates and cost to the taxpayer.</p><p>As shown in the State of the Estate Report 2015-16 published in February 2017, total vacant space represents 1.4% of the entire Central Estate, a drop of 2% from 2014–15. This is well below the average in the private sector of 8.9%.</p><p>No buildings appear on the unit’s electronic property system as vacant in the Mid-Sussex area. The buildings listed below are currently listed for disposal in the West Sussex region. There are no other records marked as surplus, or offering vacant space in West Sussex, or the Mid-Sussex constituency:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Property Name</p></td><td><p>Address</p></td><td><p>Department</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>CHICHESTER COMBINED COURT<br><br></p></td><td><p>SOUTHGATE, CHICHESTER, WEST SUSSEX, PO19 1SX</p></td><td><p>Ministry of Justice<br><br><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>CHICHESTER MAGISTRATES COURT<br><br></p></td><td><p>MARKET AVENUE, CHICHESTER, WEST SUSSEX, PO19 1YE</p></td><td><p><br>Ministry of Justice<br><br><br><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-12T10:19:02.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767398/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767398/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-09","Government Departments: Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many buildings owned by government departments are empty in (a) West Sussex and (b) Mid Sussex constituency; which those buildings are; to which departments those buildings belong; and what plans he has for the future use of those buildings.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","106506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767399","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Public Records Act (1958) requires central government departments, and certain other public bodies, to identify records of historical value and transfer them for permanent preservation to The National Archives, or to another appointed place of deposit. In 2013 the government began its move towards releasing records when they are 20 years old, instead of 30. We are currently in the middle of the transition from 20 to 30 years, with 2 years’ worth of government records being transferred each year until 2022.</p><p> </p><p>In accordance with Section 3(4) of The Public Records Act, departments may retain records if ‘they are required for administrative purposes or ought to be retained for any other special reason’. The Advisory Council on National Records and Archives is an independent body established by The Public Records Act that advises the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport on issues related to transfer of public records that are over 20 years old. Departments apply to the Advisory Council giving their reasons to retain records using the commonly cited grounds for retention, set-out in guidance published by The National Archives (link below). The Advisory Council will then make a recommendation to the Secretary of State, who signals her approval by issuing a Retention Instrument which allows departments to legally retain their records for a specified period of time.</p><p> </p><p>Records transferred to The National Archives will be open at transfer, unless exempt under Freedom of Information legislation. Access to closed records is considered under the provisions of the Freedom of Information Act, Environmental Information Regulations and the Data Protection Act.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance: http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/information-management/retention.pdf</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-12T16:18:03.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767399/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767399/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Government Departments: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the Government's policy is on the grounds on which government files are allowed to be exempt from the 30 year rule.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","106722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767400","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-16","<p>The effect of the local housing allowance freeze on the rate at which housing benefit recipients fall into arrears and become homeless has not been assessed. There is currently no clear evidence to suggest that the LHA freeze is contributing to increased arrears or homelessness.</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics show that the number of homelessness acceptances in England has decreased slightly over the past year and the figures are very similar to the homelessness acceptances when the freeze commenced.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-16T12:29:26.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767400/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767400/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-09","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the freezing of the rate of local housing allowance on the rate at which housing benefit recipients (a) fall into rent arrears and (b) become homeless.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767401","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-17T11:28:51.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767401/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767401/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount of corporation tax revenue lost from unlicensed pet sales in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","106737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767402","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-17","<p>The current legal framework limits the VAT exemptions the Government can apply. The Government does maintain several VAT reliefs to aid purchases of defibrillators. These include VAT refunds of purchases made by local authorities and VAT relief for purchases made through voluntary contributions which are donated to eligible charities or the NHS.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-17T11:29:50.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767402/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767402/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Defibrillators: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of removing value added tax from community-purchased defibrillators.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","106749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767403","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Treasury and the Department for Communities and Local Government routinely publish information on the take-up and the total value of support provided through the Help to Buy schemes. This information is readily available in the public domain.</p><p> </p><p>The following links provide the latest information on the government spend in each region and income group.</p><p> </p><p>Home Equity Loan:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/647605/20170928_HTB_EL_and_HTB_NewBuy_statistical_release.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/647605/20170928_HTB_EL_and_HTB_NewBuy_statistical_release.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Mortgage Guarantee Scheme:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/648018/H2B_MGS_Official_Statistics_Publication_-_September_17.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/648018/H2B_MGS_Official_Statistics_Publication_-_September_17.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-12T10:57:26.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767403/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767403/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been spent from the public purse on Help to Buy in each region of England; and how many beneficiaries in each income group there have been from the spend in each such region.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767404","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government recognises the vitally important work the charity sector does in the UK, which is why we currently provide tax relief to charities and donors worth over £5 billion per year, including over £1.2 billion for Gift Aid alone. The Government is also committed to supporting small charities to become more independent, resilient and sustainable. Recent work includes the announcement of a further three years of the Small Charities Fundraising Training Programme and work to explore the role of small charities in public services. On the 15th December the country will celebrate the second Local Charities Day highlighting the fantastic work of small, local charities.</p><p> </p><p>Smaller charities will also benefit from recent changes to the Gift Aid Small Donations Scheme (GASDS) that allows eligible charities and community amateur sports clubs to claim top-up payments on small donations made by cash or contactless technology of £20 or less. The rules were simplified and the maximum annual donation GASDS limit was increased to £8,000, allowing charities to now claim up to £2,000 per year in payments.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-12T14:10:36.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767404/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767404/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Charities: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps he has taken to support small local charities.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","106538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767405","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>HM Treasury reviews a number of business cases relating to free school site acquisitions. A record of instances where we have not been able to approve part or all of a business case could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-12T10:21:47.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767405/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767405/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Free Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many sites approved for purchase for free schools by the Education Skills Funding Agency have been refused funding by his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","106496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767406","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The introduction of Minimum Unit Pricing in England and Wales remains under review. The Government awaits the outcome of the Scotch Whisky Association's decision to appeal the decision of the Scottish Courts and the impact of the implementation of this policy in Scotland.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-12T10:29:48.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767406/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767406/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Alcoholic Drinks: Minimum Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with Ministers of the Welsh Government on the fiscal implications of that Government's plans to introduce minimum unit pricing for alcohol products.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","106458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767407","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The government is committed to supporting businesses in the UK to invest and improve productivity.</p><p> </p><p>The government has introduced the Apprenticeship Levy and are committed to delivering 3 million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020. We have also announced the most ambitious post-16 reforms since the introduction of A levels 70 years ago.</p><p> </p><p>The government wants the UK to be the best place to start and grow a digital business. As part of this we have announced £13 million worth of funding to create a private sector-led Productivity Council.</p><p> </p><p>Revenue expenditure on provision of skills, services and software is normally fully tax deductible in the year it is purchased, receiving relief more quickly than expenditure eligible for capital allowances.</p><p> </p><p>The government keeps all tax reliefs under review and any proposal for future changes to a relief must be assessed for its effectiveness, wider economic impact, ability to stand-up against abuse and the cost to the exchequer.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-12T12:58:28.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767407/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767407/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Capital Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of extending the scope of investment allowances to include encouragement for investment in software, services and skills as well as conventional capital procurements.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","106559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767408","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>It is the intention of the UK Government to preserve financial services market access for Gibraltar into the UK. This will require mutual confidence in regulatory and supervisory structures, and will reflect the level of cooperation in this area. The Chief Minister of Gibraltar has confirmed that Gibraltar will meet UK standards of regulation, supervision and enforcement consistent with global standards which will allow its important financial sector to maintain its access to the UK. The UK Government and the Government of Gibraltar are in ongoing discussions on how to achieve this, looking first at insurance where cross-border trade is most significant.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-12T11:00:55.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767408/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767408/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Financial Services: Gibraltar","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on whether financial services providers located in Gibraltar should have barrier-free access to the UK market after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","106561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767409","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-16","<p>The government is committed to ensuring that people have access to good-quality, free-to-client, impartial guidance on money, pensions and debt. The Financial Guidance and Claims Bill will create a new guidance body which will merge the functions of The Pensions Advisory Service, Pension Wise and the Money Advice Service. The single financial guidance body will simplify the existing public financial guidance landscape, making it easier for people to access information and guidance and help them make effective financial decisions.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-16T12:20:57.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767409/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767409/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Consumer Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans the Government has to ensure that effective guidance is available to consumers in respect of money, pensions and debt.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","106599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767410","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The government announced at Budget 2016, that Climate Change Levy rates for gas and electricity would be rebalanced to a 1:1 ratio by 2025, to reflect recent data on the fuel mix used in electricity generation. The Treasury have had constructive dialogue with liquid petroleum gas suppliers on the impacts of the policy changes on the off-gas grid market.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-12T10:30:44.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767410/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767410/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Liquefied Petroleum Gas: Climate Change Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the likelihood that off-gas grid businesses will switch to higher carbon fuels when the climate change levy on liquid petroleum gas increases up to (a) 2019 and (b) 2025.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","106689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767411","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-17","<p>A large proportion of the Treasury’s work is in some way related to exiting the European Union and this fluctuates over time as it interacts with Treasury’s other priorities. It is not possible, therefore, to accurately determine the proportion of the Treasury’s workforce engaged on EU Exit work at any one time.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-10-17T13:45:48.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767411/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767411/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767412","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>As announced in September, for 2018/19, we will no longer have an across-the-board policy of 1% average basic pay awards. Before we make final decisions on pay awards, we will seek the views of the independent Pay Review Bodies including the NHSPRB which sets the pay award for nurses and other Agenda for Change staff. The Pay Review Bodies will consider evidence on how we ensure we attract and retain the very best people within our public services.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-12T10:22:57.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767412/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767412/answer",,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-09","Nurses: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to provide additional ring-fenced funding from the public purse for pay rises over one per cent for nurses.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767413","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-27","<p>It is expected that the review will present an interim report to the Communities Secretary and the Home Secretary before the end of the year, and a final report no later than Spring 2018. The Government will consider and respond to Dame Judith Hackitt’s recommendations.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-27T11:17:00.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767413/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767413/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Building Regulations and Fire Safety Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects the independent review on building regulations and fire safety to publish guidance.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767414","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department does not hold data on the housing needs of travellers. It is the responsibility of local authorities to assess all local housing needs, including those of travellers.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-12T13:05:54.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767414/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767414/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what data his Department holds on the housing needs of Travellers who conform to the revised definition of Gypsy Travellers as set out in the Planning policy for Traveller sites 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767415","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>My officials are in contact with Barnet Council about the proposed road works which could impact on the War memorial in Golders Green. The Council have reiterated that moving the memorial would not happen without proper consultation and have confirmed that there has been no consultation on anything specific about the site.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-17T10:10:40.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767415/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767415/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","War Memorials: Barnet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with Barnet Council on ensuring that the war memorial that contains its Jewish history will not be moved due to proposed road works.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767416","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>Within the London Borough of Camden, the demolition of the National Temperance Hospital main building has occurred together with the partial demolition of the National Temperance Hospital Insul Wing. No other demolitions have been completed along the rest of the route.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T15:14:46.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767416/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767416/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Housing: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many properties in (a) the London Borough of Camden and (b) the UK have been demolished as a consequence of High Speed Rail 2.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767417","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-13","<p>We have already taken steps to help local authorities tackle unfair practices by private parking operators, including the banning of wheel clamping and towing.</p><p>My Department is also considering reforms of the private parking sector and we are keen to ensure motorists get fair treatment from private parking companies.</p><p>We welcome Sir Greg Knight’s Private Members’ Bill that seeks to create an independent code of practice for private parking companies. We look forward to reading Sir Greg’s recommendations.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-13T16:24:20.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767417/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767417/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Parking: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to strengthen the powers given to local authorities to regulate private car parks.","true","Biography information for Giles Watling","Clacton","Giles Watling","106544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767418","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>Local authorities contemplating the use of their compulsory purchase powers to acquire land and properties should consider, amongst other things, whether there is a compelling case in the public interest for doing so. They should also take account of government's guidance on the compulsory purchase process, which was published in October 2015.</p><p>The Local Government Act 1999 (Part 1, Section 3) requires an authority to carry out the functions designated to it in accordance with the ‘best value duty’. This requires that &quot;A best value authority must make arrangements to secure continuous improvement in the way in which its functions are exercised, having regard to a combination of economy, efficiency and effectiveness”. The duty applies to the full range of an authority’s activities.</p><p>Local authorities have the freedom to borrow and invest, including in land and property purchases, without government consent, provided that their borrowing is affordable. Control is exercised through four statutory codes that local authorities are required to have regard to, two prepared by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy (CIPFA) and two prepared by DCLG. This framework is known as the “Prudential System”. We are currently working with CIPFA to revise the statutory codes and guidance and the intention is for these to be in place early in 2018.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-17T17:05:33.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767418/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767418/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what criteria local authorities must consider when deciding to purchase private land and properties.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","106527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767419","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>Local authorities have powers under sections 76 to 79 of the Building Act 1984 to require the owners of buildings in a dangerous state of disrepair to take such action as required to remove the danger or to demolish the building. If the owner refuses to do so the local authority itself may take the necessary action.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-17T17:14:41.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767419/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767419/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Private Property: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance is available to local authorities on dealing with private properties in a state of disrepair that may cause structural damage to adjacent properties.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","106528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767420","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning. Staff within the EU Exit team lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across my Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-17T10:34:01.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767420/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767420/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767421","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-27","<p>The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government appointed the independent Grenfell Recovery Taskforce on 26 July 2017 to support and challenge the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea as they develop and implement a long-term recovery plan following the Grenfell Tower fire, and to assure him of progress. He asked the Taskforce to provide an initial report by the end of October. It will include the Taskforce's findings on how the Council is developing and delivering its recovery plan, how it is engaging with the community, its progress in addressing the immediate housing needs arising from the fire and improving housing management, and whether the right leadership and governance arrangements are in place across the Council.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-27T11:48:37.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767421/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767421/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Grenfell Recovery Taskforce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the scope is of the Independent Grenfell Recovery Taskforce initial report that is planned for completion by the end of October 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767422","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-18","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts in 2016 for enforcement offences (for which information is held centrally) under the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 and Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990, can be viewed in the table attached. This information is held by the Ministry of Justice.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-18T14:48:05.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767422/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767422/answer","Defendants proceeded against.xls","Defendants proceeded against.xls","defendants proceeded against ","defendants proceeded against ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767422/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Planning Permission: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of prosecutions that have been brought for unacceptable breach of planning control in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767423","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>While we do not currently plan to review the Local Authorities (Executive Arrangements) (Meetings and Access to Information) (England) Regulations 2012, we are clear that council decision-taking must be transparent and open.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-17T10:08:16.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767423/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767423/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Local Authorities (Executive Arrangements) (Meetings and Access to Information) (England) Regulations 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will review the Local Authorities (Executive Arrangements) (Meetings and Access to Information) (England) Regulations 2012; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767425","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>I can confirm that 31 local authorities have been in touch with DCLG regarding work to ensure fire safety in tower blocks. We have been clear that we expect building owners to fund fire safety measures, but councils should contact us if they have any concerns about funding fire safety works.</p><p>Where works are necessary to ensure the fire safety of a building, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent them going ahead. It is a matter for local authorities to communicate with their residents what work is being proposed.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-12T15:55:07.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767425/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767425/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","High Rise Flats: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the 31 local authorities are that have requested additional funding for tower block safety.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767426","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>I can confirm that six local authorities have been asked for further detailed information regarding work to ensure fire safety in tower blocks, following initial conversations with DCLG. We have been clear that we expect building owners to fund fire safety measures, but councils should contact us if they have any concerns about funding fire safety works.</p><p>Where works are necessary to ensure the fire safety of a building, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent them going ahead. It is a matter for local authorities to communicate with their residents what work is being proposed, and as such I cannot provide the names of specific local authorities.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-12T13:05:15.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767426/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767426/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","High Rise Flats: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the five local authorities are that have been asked for further information on their application for requested additional funding for tower block safety.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767427","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>Through our policies, including the Supported Housing programme and Disabled Facilities Grant programme, my department is helping those in society get the help and support they need to live independently and be part of their communities.</p><p>Our Near Neighbours, and Community-based English Language programmes will also help to reduce loneliness in target populations through their work.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-16T15:50:12.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767427/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767427/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Loneliness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to reduce loneliness in (a) England, (b) West Yorkshire, (c) Kirklees and (d) Colne Valley.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","106750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767428","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>This Government is committed to preventing and reducing homelessness in England. That is why we are aiming to halve rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminate it altogether by 2027. We will set up a rough sleeping and homelessness taskforce and pilot a Housing First approach to tackle rough sleeping.</p><p>We are implementing the most ambitious legislative reform in decades, the Homelessness Reduction Act, to prevent people becoming homeless in the first place by ensuring more people get the help they need earlier.</p><p>We are also investing over £550 million until 2020 to prevent and reduce homelessness and rough sleeping, including through our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme. This is supporting 84 projects working across England to deliver an end-to-end approach to homelessness prevention.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-17T10:14:06.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767428/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767428/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to reduce homelessness in (a) England, (b) West Yorkshire, (c) Kirklees and (d) Colne Valley.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","106751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767429","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>In the last financial year, two private parking companies had been suspended from receiving data from the Driver and Vehicle and Licensing Agency (DVLA) because they had been found not to follow the accredited trade association's code of practice.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-17T14:59:23.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767429/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767429/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Parking: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many private parking companies have had access to DVLA data suspended because they have been found not to follow the trade association's code of practice.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767430","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>Time spent in temporary accommodation ensures no family is without a roof over their head. The Government is assisting areas to ensure that families spend no longer than 6 weeks in B&amp;Bs, which includes protecting and maintaining the homelessness prevention funding at £315 million. We have also replaced Department of Work and Pension’s Temporary Accommodation Management Fee with a Flexible Homelessness Support Grant which local authorities can use more strategically to prevent and tackle homelessness. This amounts to £402 million over the two years from 2017/18.</p><p>While the number of households in temporary accommodation is below the 2004 peak, the law is clear that households with dependent children should only be accommodated in B&amp;B in an emergency and for no longer than six weeks, which commences when the household moves in.</p><p>Local authorities have a duty to ensure that any accommodation provided for a homeless household under the homelessness legislation must be suitable.</p><p>Part B (Fire safety) of the Building Regulations sets requirements for fire safety where building work takes place, typically including the erection, extension or alteration of a building. Guidance is issued by the Secretary of State in Approved Documents, specifically Approved Document B (Fire Safety) Volume 1 (dwellinghouses) and Volume 2 (Buildings other than dwellinghouses).</p><p>The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 also applies to premises that provide sleeping accommodation, other than where they are a private home. The Fire Safety Order requires a ‘responsible person’ (usually the owner, employer or landlord) to carry out and review regularly a fire risk assessment of a premises to ensure adequate and appropriate fire safety measures are in place to manage the risk that lives could be lost in the event of a fire.</p><p>The Government has produced guidance to help those with fire safety responsibilities in sleeping accommodation to comply with the provisions of the Fire Safety Order – <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fire-safety-risk-assessment-sleeping-accommodation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fire-safety-risk-assessment-sleeping-accommodation</a>. The extent to which the fire protection measures in place in any particular building comply with these provisions is a matter for the responsible person’s risk assessment.</p><p>DCLG publishes regular statistics on rough sleeping, statutory homelessness, temporary accommodation and homelessness prevention and relief, including the numbers of households in B&amp;B for over 6 weeks. These are published at national, London and local authority level. The latest statistics can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a>.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","106734","2017-10-17T10:05:31.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767430/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767430/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Temporary Accommodation: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department issues to local authorities to ensure that (a) private hostels, (b) bed and breakfasts and (c) other unsupported temporary accommodation providers have adequate fire safety measures.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767431","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Government is committed to preventing and reducing homelessness. The timely commencement of the Homelessness Reduction Act will ensure that local authorities intervene at earlier stages to prevent homelessness. It is our intention to commence the Act in April 2018. On Monday 16 October I updated the House on a commitment I made to fund the administrative costs of the additional new duties contained within the Act in line with the new burdens doctrine. Following further discussions with local authorities, the Government is providing an additional £11.7 million in new burdens funding taking the total amount from £61million to £72.7 million.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-17T10:18:23.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767431/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767431/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to bring into force the Homelessness Reduction Act 2017; and whether he plans to provide additional funding to councils to ensure the performance of their responsibilities under that Act.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767432","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government published the list of local authorities that notified the Department that they have re-billed each of the three rates relief. It is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-rates-relief-schemes-2017-rebilling-progress" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-rates-relief-schemes-2017-rebilling-progress</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-17T10:12:15.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767432/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767432/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether it remains his Department's policy to publish a list of local authorities that have notified that they have re-billed for each of the three rates relief schemes; and what the reasons are for the time taken to publish that data.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767433","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>We have not made such estimates as the Mayor has overall responsibility for affordable housing policy and delivery in London. However data does show that in the first year of the new Mayoral administration there were no new homes for social rent started with GLA support – the first year on record this has fallen to zero.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-17T17:10:11.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767433/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767433/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Social Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of homes for social rent that will be completed in (a) London and (b) England in (i) 2017, (ii) 2018, (iii) 2019 and (iv) 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767434","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-17T17:08:14.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767434/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767434/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will place in the Library copies of all correspondence between his Department and the Local Government Association in the last three years relating to residential fire safety.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767435","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>My Department has not commissioned any research relating to devolution in Yorkshire. It is for local leaders to put forward any devolution proposal on an appropriate geography and commanding wide support. We would welcome and consider any such proposal that did not</p><p>cut across the Sheffield City Region deal.</p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-10-17T12:10:16.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767435/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767435/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Devolution: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will place in the Library the results of the research commissioned by his Department relating to a One Yorkshire devolution deal.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767436","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-17","<p>Time spent in temporary accommodation ensures no family is without a roof over their head. The Government is assisting areas to ensure that families spend no longer than 6 weeks in B&amp;Bs, which includes protecting and maintaining the homelessness prevention funding at £315 million. We have also replaced Department of Work and Pension’s Temporary Accommodation Management Fee with a Flexible Homelessness Support Grant which local authorities can use more strategically to prevent and tackle homelessness. This amounts to £402 million over the two years from 2017/18.</p><p>While the number of households in temporary accommodation is below the 2004 peak, the law is clear that households with dependent children should only be accommodated in B&amp;B in an emergency and for no longer than six weeks, which commences when the household moves in.</p><p>Local authorities have a duty to ensure that any accommodation provided for a homeless household under the homelessness legislation must be suitable.</p><p>Part B (Fire safety) of the Building Regulations sets requirements for fire safety where building work takes place, typically including the erection, extension or alteration of a building. Guidance is issued by the Secretary of State in Approved Documents, specifically Approved Document B (Fire Safety) Volume 1 (dwellinghouses) and Volume 2 (Buildings other than dwellinghouses).</p><p>The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 also applies to premises that provide sleeping accommodation, other than where they are a private home. The Fire Safety Order requires a ‘responsible person’ (usually the owner, employer or landlord) to carry out and review regularly a fire risk assessment of a premises to ensure adequate and appropriate fire safety measures are in place to manage the risk that lives could be lost in the event of a fire.</p><p>The Government has produced guidance to help those with fire safety responsibilities in sleeping accommodation to comply with the provisions of the Fire Safety Order – <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fire-safety-risk-assessment-sleeping-accommodation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fire-safety-risk-assessment-sleeping-accommodation</a>. The extent to which the fire protection measures in place in any particular building comply with these provisions is a matter for the responsible person’s risk assessment.</p><p>DCLG publishes regular statistics on rough sleeping, statutory homelessness, temporary accommodation and homelessness prevention and relief, including the numbers of households in B&amp;B for over 6 weeks. These are published at national, London and local authority level. The latest statistics can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a>.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","106761","2017-10-17T10:05:31.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767436/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767436/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Bed and Breakfast Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, in how many cases during (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017 homeless families were unlawfully  placed in bed and breakfast accommodation for more than six weeks.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767437","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>The increase in spend in March was due to the Regional Mayoral Elections, accounting for 73 per cent of the spend in that month.</p><p>The objective of the campaign was to raise public awareness ahead of the regional elections held on 4 May 2017.</p><p>This is in support of the Government's aim to enable a shift in power from central to local government, with decentralisation bringing power closer to local communities. My department wants cities to have more control over transport, housing, skills and healthcare with elected mayors.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","105442","2017-10-16T16:10:41.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767437/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767437/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Department for Communities and Local Government: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 21 September 2017 to Question 3402, on Department for Communities and Local Government: advertising, what the reasons are for the increase in social media advertising spending in March 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767438","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-27","<p>Regulations and planning reforms encourage the use of renewables without mandating any particular technology. Mandating a particular renewable technology, such as solar panels, may not be appropriate for all building types in all areas. Building regulations are deliberately couched in performance terms, allowing builders, local councils and architects the flexibility to select from a range of renewable energy technologies to suit the potentially unique circumstances of a particular development.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-27T11:46:16.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767438/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767438/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Housing: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that solar panels form part of the infrastructure for all new buildings.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","106770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767439","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>As the Secretary of State announced at the National Housing Federation Conference on 19 September, we will bring forward a Green Paper on social housing in England.</p><p>The Green Paper will be a wide-ranging review of the issues facing the sector and the most substantial report of its kind for a generation.</p><p>The Housing Minister’s engagement with social housing tenants over the coming months will feed into the scope and content of the Green Paper.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-12T15:57:11.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767439/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767439/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Grenfell Tower Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 September 2017 to Question 9205, on the Grenfell Tower inquiry, how he plans to report the findings from the exercise described in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767440","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>Our priority is to ensure that all households from Grenfell Tower and Grenfell Walk are provided with a permanent home within a year. The Government is working closely with the Council to deliver this as swiftly as possible, but it's important to get this right and ensure residents have choice over their housing options and are given the time they need.</p><p>Housing allocations officers from the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea have carried out housing needs assessments for those being rehoused. Family Liaison Officers and keyworkers are also in place to ensure the bereaved and survivors are able to access support to meet their wider needs.</p><p>The latest figures I have from the Council, as of 9 October, show that 111 households have accepted an offer of either temporary or permanent accommodation. 54 have now moved in; of which 44 households have already moved in to temporary accommodation, and 10 households have moved into permanent accommodation.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-12T16:00:20.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767440/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767440/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017, to Question 9297, on Grenfell Tower: fire, how many families have been rehoused; how many families have received an offer of housing which they have not accepted; by when the Government aims for all families to have been re-housed; what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the re-housing process does not take longer than necessary; and what mechanisms are in place for people affected by the fire to make their needs clear.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767441","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-27","<p>The latest complete information on the testing of Aluminium Composite Material cladding samples is contained in the summary advice published on 5 September (available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing</a>), which sets out the results of screening tests and the seven large-scale system tests conducted over the summer. It includes the numbers of buildings tested, broken down by filler material and type of insulation used.</p><p>The detailed test results from each of the seven large-scale system tests conducted at the Building Research Establishment are available on the Building Safety Programme webpage at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","106716","2017-10-27T11:22:13.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767441/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767441/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 21 September 2017 to Question 9597, what core materials were found within the 554 samples of aluminium composite material cladding that were tested.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767442","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-27","<p>The latest complete information on the testing of Aluminium Composite Material cladding samples is contained in the summary advice published on 5 September (available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing</a>), which sets out the results of screening tests and the seven large-scale system tests conducted over the summer. It includes the numbers of buildings tested, broken down by filler material and type of insulation used.</p><p>The detailed test results from each of the seven large-scale system tests conducted at the Building Research Establishment are available on the Building Safety Programme webpage at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/building-safety-programme</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","106715","2017-10-27T11:22:13.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767442/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767442/answer",,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2017 to Question 7185, on high rise flats: fire prevention, if he will publish the results of those tests.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","106716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767443","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department has made no formal assessment of the costs. However, we meet regularly with a range of cultural institutions, including sponsored museums and sector bodies, in which we discuss both financial and security arrangements. We are aware that cultural institutions have and are taking steps to ensure security measures are in place. The Tourism Industry Emergency Response Group also convenes after incidents to evaluate impact and discuss the future response.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-10-16T10:22:22.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767443/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767443/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Terrorism: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the additional costs incurred by cultural institutions as a result of extra security after recent acts of terrorism in London.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767444","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>Through the Digital Economy Act (2017), we have created the requirement for commercial providers of online pornography to have robust age verification controls to prevent under 18s accessing this material.</p><p> </p><p>Our aim is to bring these powers into force within 12 months of the Act receiving Royal Assent (27 April 2017).</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T12:10:18.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767444/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767444/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Pornography: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to stop access for those under 18-years of age to online porn sites.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767445","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government are responsibly preparing for a range of outcomes to ensure we have a smooth exit from the EU. The Government is engaging with businesses in every sector and region of the UK economy in order to understand the challenges and opportunities that may impact them in the coming months and years. <strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106503 ; 106673","2017-10-12T16:11:53.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767445/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767445/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department has taken to prepare for the possibility that the UK might leave the EU without having agreed a deal with the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767446","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department does not hold information on superfast broadband take-up percentage by regions. The 2016 Ofcom Connected Nations report showed average take up percentage by home nation to be:</p><p> </p><p>England - 32%</p><p>Northern Ireland - 34%</p><p>Wales - 24%</p><p>Scotland - 27%</p><p> </p><p>Take up percentages of premises covered by BDUK projects can be found in the 'Table of local broadband projects' on the department's website : https://www.gov.uk/guidance/broadband-delivery-uk#superfast-broadband-programme.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T13:14:27.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767446/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767446/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the percentage take-up of superfast broadband is in each region of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767447","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government are responsibly preparing for a range of outcomes to ensure we have a smooth exit from the EU. The Government is engaging with businesses in every sector and region of the UK economy in order to understand the challenges and opportunities that may impact them in the coming months and years. <strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106517 ; 106673","2017-10-12T16:11:53.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767447/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767447/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what preparations her Department is making for the possibility of negotiations on the UK leaving the EU resulting in no agreement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","106503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767448","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>Having a recognised process around handling vulnerability disclosures is an important part of any organisation’s security maturity. A bug bounty program similar to that rolled out in the US can be part of that process, but initially it is important to develop a mature way of receiving, triaging and remediating those vulnerabilities disclosed to UK Government. NCSC are currently running a private pilot for handling vulnerability disclosure ahead of rolling it out HMG-wide.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-12T10:17:46.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767448/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767448/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-09","Cybercrime: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of adopting in the UK a programme similar to the US Department of Defense trial bug bounty programme organised through the US Digital Service on the HackerOne platform.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","106493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767449","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-12","<p>Qatar is FIFA's agreed host for the 2022 World Cup, and therefore no assessment has been made.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-12T14:45:49.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767449/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767449/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Football: World Cup","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has made an assessment of the potential capacity of England to host the 2022 World Cup; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767450","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government are responsibly preparing for a range of outcomes to ensure we have a smooth exit from the EU. The Government is engaging with businesses in every sector and region of the UK economy in order to understand the challenges and opportunities that may impact them in the coming months and years. <strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106503 ; 106517","2017-10-12T16:11:53.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767450/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767450/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the potential effect of the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU resulting in no deal on the number of jobs in the technology, culture and heritage sectors in the UK; what the evidential basis is for that estimate; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","106673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767451","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-17","<p>Staff within the DCMS EU Team lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and related issues. Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analyses on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department's other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-17T15:28:50.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767451/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767451/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in her Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767452","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>We do not hold information on current average download speed by region. The 2016 Ofcom Connected Nations report showed that the home nations had average download speeds of:</p><p> </p><p>England - 38Mbit/s</p><p>Northern Ireland - 34Mbit/s</p><p>Wales - 29Mbit/s</p><p>Scotland - 35Mbit/s</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T13:15:17.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767452/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767452/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the average download speed for fixed broadband services is in each region of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767453","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-17","<p>We do not hold information on superfast broadband take-up percentage by constituency.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-17T15:32:34.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767453/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767453/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many premises in each parliamentary constituency in the UK have taken up a superfast broadband connection.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767454","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Data Protection Bill will require the Information Commissioner to prepare statutory data sharing and direct marketing codes of practice. The Commissioner will be required to submit these codes to the Secretary of State and the codes must subsequently be laid before Parliament for consideration. The Secretary of State may also require the Commissioner to prepare additional codes giving guidance on good practice in other data processing areas. Through regular dialogue, the government will work with the Commissioner to identify other data processing activities and sectors where non-statutory guidance would be of benefit and should be developed.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-17T15:37:18.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767454/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767454/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Data Protection: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what (a) oversight and (b) powers the Government will have in relation to guidance issued by the Information Commissioner on the application of the General Data Protection Regulation.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","106646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767455","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are consulting on introducing a social media code of practice as part of the Internet Safety Strategy which was published on 11 October.</p><p> </p><p>As laid out in the Digital Economy Act 2017, the code will seek to ensure that providers offer adequate online safety policies, introduce minimum standards and metrics and ensure regular review and monitoring. The code will not cover unlawful content or conduct, such as terrorist material or threats of violence, which the legal framework already addresses.</p><p> </p><p>Government will continue to consult with stakeholders in the tech industry on the details of the code of practice before its introduction in 2018.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106634 ; 106635 ; 106637","2017-10-16T08:59:15.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767455/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767455/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans she has for the code of practice for online social media platforms to apply to conduct which involves threats of violence and terrorism.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767456","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are consulting on introducing a social media code of practice as part of the Internet Safety Strategy which was published on 11 October.</p><p> </p><p>As laid out in the Digital Economy Act 2017, the code will seek to ensure that providers offer adequate online safety policies, introduce minimum standards and metrics and ensure regular review and monitoring. The code will not cover unlawful content or conduct, such as terrorist material or threats of violence, which the legal framework already addresses.</p><p> </p><p>Government will continue to consult with stakeholders in the tech industry on the details of the code of practice before its introduction in 2018.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106633 ; 106635 ; 106637","2017-10-16T08:59:15.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767456/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767456/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to commence consultation on the code of practice for online social media platforms.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767457","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-12","<p>As I made clear at Departmental Oral Questions on 14 September, I am determined that the gambling industry acknowledges its social responsibilities, including properly funding the work undertaken by GambleAware, and other organisations, on research, education and treatment for gambling-related harm.</p><p> </p><p>The industry currently contributes over £8 million per year to GambleAware. GambleAware is seeking to increase this to £10 million per year in line with work that has been done by the Responsible Gambling Strategy Board (RGSB) to cost the short term work of delivering the National Responsible Gambling Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The industry must step up and fulfill their obligations under these new targets.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-12T14:42:37.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767457/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767457/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Gambling: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what her policy is on the introduction of a compulsory levy on licensed gambling businesses to help treat problem gamblers.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767458","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are consulting on introducing a social media code of practice as part of the Internet Safety Strategy which was published on 11 October.</p><p> </p><p>As laid out in the Digital Economy Act 2017, the code will seek to ensure that providers offer adequate online safety policies, introduce minimum standards and metrics and ensure regular review and monitoring. The code will not cover unlawful content or conduct, such as terrorist material or threats of violence, which the legal framework already addresses.</p><p> </p><p>Government will continue to consult with stakeholders in the tech industry on the details of the code of practice before its introduction in 2018.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106633 ; 106634 ; 106637","2017-10-16T08:59:15.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767458/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767458/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what guidance her Department plans to give on criteria to be used by online social media platforms when applying the code of practice to determine whether an abusive or threatening incident has reached the criminal threshold.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767459","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are consulting on introducing a social media code of practice as part of the Internet Safety Strategy which was published on 11 October.</p><p> </p><p>As laid out in the Digital Economy Act 2017, the code will seek to ensure that providers offer adequate online safety policies, introduce minimum standards and metrics and ensure regular review and monitoring. The code will not cover unlawful content or conduct, such as terrorist material or threats of violence, which the legal framework already addresses.</p><p> </p><p>Government will continue to consult with stakeholders in the tech industry on the details of the code of practice before its introduction in 2018.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","106633 ; 106634 ; 106635","2017-10-16T08:59:15.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767459/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767459/answer",,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-09","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whom her Department plans to consult before introducing the code of practice for online social media platforms.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767460","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 21 July 2017 to Question 5022 to the hon. Member of Arfron, (Hywel Williams).</p><p>Given that a wide range of officials from across the Ministry of Defence are working on EU exit as part of their other duties, it's not possible to provide an accurate proportion.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-16T14:52:45.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767460/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767460/answer","20170721_5022_MOD_Brexit.docx","20170721_5022_MOD_Brexit.docx","5022 - WQnA extract on MOD Brexit","5022 - WQnA extract on MOD Brexit","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767460/answer",,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-09","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767461","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-17","<p>The daily cost of core meals for UK Service personnel is set by the Armed Forces Pay Review Body at £5.74 inclusive of Value Added Tax.</p><p>The table below highlights the core meal price spent on produce and ingredients:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Breakfast </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Lunch </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Main Meal </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Food cost </strong></p></td><td><p>£1.20</p></td><td><p>£1.62</p></td><td><p>£1.97</p></td><td><p>£4.79</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>VAT @ 20% </strong></p></td><td><p>£0.24</p></td><td><p>£0.32</p></td><td><p>£0.39</p></td><td><p>£0.95</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total cost </strong></p></td><td><p>£1.44</p></td><td><p>£1.94</p></td><td><p>£2.36</p></td><td><p>£5.74</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The cost of the preparation and serving of food is included within the Ministry of Defence’s existing catering contracts. These costs are not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-17T13:57:09.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767461/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767461/answer",,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-09","Military Bases: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average cost is of preparing and serving a meal in Army barracks.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767462","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>To ensure the operational effectiveness of their Units, the Royal Navy takes food hygiene extremely seriously. Galleys are subjected to routine cleans, followed by formal inspections by individual chefs and Logistics and Executive personnel, in addition to Operational Sea Training and Flotilla inspections.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-16T14:41:22.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767462/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767462/answer",,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-09","Warships: Hygiene","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that hygiene standards are maintained in navy ship galleys.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767463","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-17","<p>There are no plans to review the decision to decommission HMS OCEAN in 2018.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-17T13:57:44.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767463/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767463/answer",,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-09","HMS Ocean","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will retain HMS Ocean for the Royal Marines after 2018.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767464","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>I am sorry, but the information requested is not available as the Department for Education does not hold data on whether parents of children in need have access to public funds.</p><p><em><br> </em></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:36:24.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767464/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767464/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children under 18-years old were classified as a child in need in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2014-15 because a parent had no recourse to public funds.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767465","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>Example menus and guidance have been developed as part of the delivery of the Childhood Obesity Plan to support early year’s settings in England. This is to provide meals and snacks in line with current government dietary recommendations for infants and children aged six months to four years. The government will publish the menus and guidance in due course. Separate Voluntary Food and Drink Guidelines are already available for early years settings to help them meet the nutritional needs of children aged one to five.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:39:46.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767465/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767465/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Pre-school Education: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the voluntary guidelines for food in early-years settings highlighted in the Childhood Obesity Plan will be published.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","106650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767466","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The childhood obesity plan, published in August 2016, mentions that we will update the School Food Standards in light of refreshed government dietary recommendations. We are currently reflecting on the best course of action and further announcements will be made in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:38:06.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767466/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767466/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Schools: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the refreshed school food standards highlighted in the Childhood Obesity Plan will be published; and whether those standards will reflect new requirements on dietary fibre.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","106649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767467","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>Examinations are, by their very nature, stressful but the Government has already taken steps to reduce the examination burdens upon pupils. At GCSE, we have made examinations linear, with examinations only at the end of the course of study, giving pupils at least two full years of study before they sit external examinations. At A level we have also made the examinations linear with no January assessment window, and have created a new structure that will enable students to study for two full years towards an A level without the need to take an AS level examinations at all.</p><p>In addition, the Department is taking forward various projects to support schools further, including extending a joint training pilot to train mental health leads in schools and specialist services across 1200 more schools and colleges in 20 additional Clinical Commissioning Group areas.</p><p>We are also investing £1.5 million to pilot a range of peer support programmes and approaches for schools, colleges, community groups and online.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-17T16:19:44.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767467/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767467/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Assessments: Stress","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to promote safe alleviation of stress for young people in exams times; and whether there are any initiatives that teachers who are worried about pupils can use.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767468","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-17T16:28:03.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767468/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767468/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Schools: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many nationals of other EU member states work in schools in (a) Kirklees, (b) West Yorkshire and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","106754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767469","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The data requested for Liverpool local authority and England is published in Table 5LA of the ‘Provision for children under 5 years of age’ Statistical First Release:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2017" target="_blank">Education provision: children under 5 years of age, January 2017 - GOV.UK</a>.<strong><br> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:41:14.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767469/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767469/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the take-up rate is of the 15 hours childcare offer for disadvantaged two-year olds in (a) the Liverpool city region and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","106524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767470","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Early Years Foundation Stage (EYFS) statutory framework (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-foundation-stage-framework--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-foundation-stage-framework--2</a>) sets the standards that all early years providers must meet to ensure that children learn and develop well and are kept healthy and safe. The welfare and safeguarding section in the EYFS sets the required maximum staff to child ratios. Ratio and qualification requirements apply to the total number of staff available to work directly with children. For children aged three and over, staff with a level 6 qualification supported by someone with a level 3 can operate with a 1:13 ratio, whereas staff with a level 3 supported by someone with a level 2 qualification can operate with a 1:8 ratio. There are no plans to change the requirements. We do not measure staff to child ratios, therefore it is not possible to assess trends.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:44:10.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767470/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767470/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the trend in the child-to-staff ratio in childcare and early-years settings in England.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","106522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767471","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>I am sorry, but the school governing boards are responsible for their school meals service at a local level and the department does not collect this information.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:56:26.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767471/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767471/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average cost is of preparing and serving a meal in state-funded schools.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767472","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>Workforce data can be found in the annual Early Years Census published by the Department for Education. The workforce data collected in the census relates only to private, voluntary and independent (PVI) settings and childminders. The most recent census which contains information on the graduate workforce can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016</a> (9LA).</p><p> </p><p>In maintained nursery and state-funded primary schools where 3- and 4- year olds benefit from funded early education, it is a requirement that at least one member of staff is a school teacher. Data on the number of maintained and state-funded primary schools can also be found in the census (Table 11).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-17T15:58:39.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767472/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767472/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many childcare and early-years education settings in England contain at least one qualified teacher.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","106520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767473","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Early Years Workforce Strategy published in March this year, sets out the actions we will take to attract, retain and develop the early years workforce.</p><p>The strategy includes a commitment to working with the early years sector and awarding organisations to develop new criteria for level 2 childcare qualifications.</p><p>The Department will also work with organisations specialising in SEND (special educational needs and disability) to develop a specification for early years staff who want to focus on SEND.</p><p>The strategy also includes a commitment to review the early years initial teacher training routes to make sure we are maximising the impact of the programme.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:46:14.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767473/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767473/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to improve staff qualifications in childcare and early-education settings in England.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","106521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767474","Department for Education","false","2017-10-12","<p>I wrote to the hon. Member for Liverpool, West Derby, on 10 October 2017 in response to his letter.</p><p>I very much look forward to meeting with him and the Liverpool City Cabinet Member for Children and Young People’s Services.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-12T16:25:06.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767474/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767474/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the Minister for Children and Families plans to respond to the letter dated 16 August 2017 from the hon. Member for Liverpool, West Derby on a meeting with the Liverpool City cabinet member for children and young people's services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","106556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767475","Department for Education","false","2017-10-12","<p>Pursuant to the answer to PQ10247, published on 20 September 2017, HM Treasury approval was not required for the exchange of contracts for the Bowring Sports Ground. No estimate of the cost of relocating flood defences was made prior to the exchange of contracts.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-12T16:17:11.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767475/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767475/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Schools: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 10246, whether the purchase of the Bowring Sports Ground required the approval of HM Treasury; whether an estimate of the cost of the work by the Environment Agency to relocate flood defences on that site was made prior to purchase; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","106495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767476","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>Information setting out how the Department works with partners including the Student Loans Company, to minimise fraud, including fraud in the student finance system, is published on pages 48-49 of the Department’s Consolidated annual report and accounts for year ended 31 March 2017 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfe-consolidated-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfe-consolidated-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017</a>.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-16T17:28:40.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767476/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767476/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what systems her Department has in place to prevent student loans from being claimed fraudulently.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767477","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department has not made a recent estimate of the proportion of student loans which are claimed fraudulently. However, the Student Loans Company (SLC) has made an estimate of the fraud rate in relation to student support payments (i.e payments of student loans and grants) for the financial year 2016-2017.</p><p>The SLC’s estimated fraud rate in relation to student support payments for the financial year 2016-2017 is 0.57%.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-16T17:34:50.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767477/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767477/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate her Department has made of the proportion of student loans which are claimed fraudulently.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767478","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>Parents should avoid taking their children out of school during term-time, except in exceptional circumstances. The evidence shows every extra day of school missed can affect a pupil’s chances of achieving good GCSEs, which has a lasting effect on their life chances.</p><p>We have a robust local control regime to enforce this, which enables the school or local authority to issue a penalty notice that where parents have failed to secure their child’s regular attendance at school, including if they take their child out of school for a vacation without permission.</p><p>Every local authority must draw up a Code of Conduct for issuing penalty notices, in consultation with governing bodies and head teachers in their area. The Code will set out the occasions when it will be appropriate to issue a penalty notice. This can, for example, include circumstances where a pupil is persistently late to school without a valid reason. A penalty notice must be issued in accordance with that Code.</p><p>In April 2017 the Supreme Court unanimously agreed with our position that no child should be taken out of school without good reason.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-17T09:37:48.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767478/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767478/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Truancy: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to review her Department's policy on fining parents whose children are absent from school because of term-time vacations.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","106445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767479","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for Education has four members of staff working full time in a central team co-ordinating and contributing to cross-department and cross-government work on EU exit. These staff are supported by a range of civil servants across the department who lead on specific policy areas and whose work includes, but is not limited to EU exit work.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:52:26.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767479/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767479/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in her Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767480","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>Early years workforce data can be found in the annual Early Years Census published by the Department for Education. The workforce data collected in the census relates only to private, voluntary and independent (PVI) settings and childminders. Data on the number of children in PVI settings with a qualified graduate professional can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016</a> (See Table 13).</p><p> </p><p>Children in receipt of a funded place at a maintained nursery or state-funded primary school will have contact with a qualified graduate, due to the requirements in these settings for at least one member of staff to be a school teacher.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-17T14:28:08.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767480/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767480/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in England attending funded childcare and early-education settings do not have contact with a qualified graduate professional.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","106526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767481","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>Early years initial teacher training (EYITT) was introduced in September 2013 and built on its predecessor, Early Years Professional Status. To date, over 16,000 specialist graduates have been trained.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently four EYITT routes available, including a route for graduates already employed in an early years setting. Funding is available for training course fees, with additional funding (£7,000) to enable early years employers to release an employee to participate in training. To encourage the best graduates into the early years workforce we also provide bursaries of between £2,000 and £5,000 to eligible trainees. The EYITT training routes are demand-led and we have always met the needs of EYITT providers in terms of numbers of places requested.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T17:55:08.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767481/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767481/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding has been made available for graduate training in the childcare and early-education workforce in England in each of the last five years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","106525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767482","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>Third Party applications to use the National Pupil Database (NPD) are only progressed if they are compliant with the Education Act and Data Protection Act. As part of the approvals process, officials including legal experts and senior civil servants with data expertise assess the application for public benefit, proportionality (ensuring the minimum amount of data is used to meet the purpose), legal underpinning, and that the strict information security standards have been satisfied.</p><p> </p><p>Onward data sharing of data requested by approved third-party organisations is only possible where this is made explicit within the NPD application form. The application form specifically states that the requestor ‘will not further disclose, publish or pass on the data without the prior written approval of the department’. Any additional organisation receiving any NPD data would also be required to satisfy the same security controls as the original requestor.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education typically process approximately 350 requests a year for individual level data per year. The vast majority of these do not involve onward sharing of individual level data. A full review of each underlying NPD data request to definitively quantify the number of instances which have involved sub-contracting or onward data share arrangements from an approved third-party organisation could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not charge for access to data from the National Pupil Database.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","106645","2017-10-17T16:36:31.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767482/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767482/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Pupils: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether any data extracted from the national pupil database has been transferred from an approved third-party organisation to any other organisation.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","106644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767483","Department for Education","false","2017-10-17","<p>Third Party applications to use the National Pupil Database (NPD) are only progressed if they are compliant with the Education Act and Data Protection Act. As part of the approvals process, officials including legal experts and senior civil servants with data expertise assess the application for public benefit, proportionality (ensuring the minimum amount of data is used to meet the purpose), legal underpinning, and that the strict information security standards have been satisfied.</p><p> </p><p>Onward data sharing of data requested by approved third-party organisations is only possible where this is made explicit within the NPD application form. The application form specifically states that the requestor ‘will not further disclose, publish or pass on the data without the prior written approval of the department’. Any additional organisation receiving any NPD data would also be required to satisfy the same security controls as the original requestor.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education typically process approximately 350 requests a year for individual level data per year. The vast majority of these do not involve onward sharing of individual level data. A full review of each underlying NPD data request to definitively quantify the number of instances which have involved sub-contracting or onward data share arrangements from an approved third-party organisation could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not charge for access to data from the National Pupil Database.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","106644","2017-10-17T16:36:31.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767483/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767483/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Pupils: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much income her Department derived from allowing third-party organisations to access the national pupil database.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","106645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767484","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Government is considering future participation in Erasmus as part of the European Union (EU) Exit negotiations. We see future co-operation in education programmes (as with research) as an area of mutual benefit to both the UK and the EU, provided we can agree a fair ongoing contribution.</p><p>There is, of course, a range of wider international mobility activity supported by organisations such as the British Council, UK and others. The Government has made clear many times that it values the Erasmus+ programme and international exchanges more generally and has stated publicly that the UK is committed to continuing full participation in the Erasmus+ Programme up until we leave the EU.</p><p>We will underwrite successful bids for Erasmus+, which are submitted while the UK is still a Member State, even if they are not approved until after we leave, and/or payments continue beyond the point of Exit.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-16T17:32:42.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767484/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767484/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-09","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether reciprocal funding for Erasmus students will continue after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","106641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767485","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>Defra has supported a range of research relevant to improving understanding of the effects of neonicotinoids (and other pesticides) on bees. Recently completed work includes studies on: quantifying the exposure of bumblebees to neonicotinoids and mixtures of pesticides (commenced 2013), interpreting pesticide residues in honeybees (published 2015), using radio-frequency identification devices to assess effects of pesticides on foraging bees (commenced 2013), and protection goals for bee colonies (commenced 2015).</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-18T16:33:24.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767485/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767485/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Bees: Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what research his Department has recently conducted into the effects of neonicotinoids on the health of the UK bee population.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","106549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767486","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Withdrawal Bill will convert current EU law into domestic law wherever practical, giving consumers and businesses as much certainty as possible. This includes laws relating to chemicals. The UK is strongly committed to the effective and safe management of chemicals. That will not change when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-17T14:58:09.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767486/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767486/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Chemicals: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential adequacy of the legislative framework regulating the chemicals industry when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","106551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767487","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>Defra does not hold official statistics on the number of dog breeders and pet shops operating without a licence. Defra is currently in the process of developing a new single animal activities licensing regime. The regulations will be laid in Parliament before they come into force next year. The new regime will reduce the threshold by which people will need a dog breeding licence from five litters or more per year to three litters or more per year. This should result in more dog breeders requiring a licence. The new regime will make it clear for local authorities which individual activities need to be licensed.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","106736","2017-10-18T17:44:09.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767487/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767487/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Dogs: Animal Breeding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information his Department holds on the number of dog breeding premises operating without a licence.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767488","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-23","<p>Defra is currently in the process of developing a new single animal activities licensing regime. The regulations will be laid in Parliament before they come into force next year. The regulations will be clear that anyone in the business of selling pet animals will need a licence whether this is carried out from a traditional pet shop or online. Commercial pet animal advertisers will also be required to include certain information in their advertisements including details of their licence.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-23T13:13:53.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767488/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767488/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the single animal activities licensing regime to regulate online sales.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767489","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-16","<p>Over 80% of Defra’s agenda is affected by the UK’s departure from the European Union and as a result, many roles across the Defra group are now supporting EU exit-related work, either directly or indirectly. We continue to keep our resourcing plans under review, focusing both on recruitment and increasing the capability of new and existing staff.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-16T09:39:46.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767489/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767489/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767490","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Environment Agency has no record of any contact from the Education Skills Funding Agency prior to December 2015. The Environment Agency was contacted by the Education Skills Funding Agency in December 2015 regarding the potential purchase of land in Bowring Sports Ground to build a new school on the site.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency met the Education Skills Funding Agency in March 2016 to discuss their proposals and to provide planning advice. No change to the flood defences was proposed at that time. The proposal to relocate flood defences on the Bowring Sports Ground site was first put forward in June 2017 by Robert West Architects and discussions with them are ongoing.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Environment Agency requires developers to demonstrate that their proposals do not increase flood risk. The Environment Agency is a statutory consultee in the planning process. The Environment Agency will not support any application which does not include an adequate flood risk assessment. The Environment Agency will assess detailed proposals and a flood risk assessment in relation to this application, once provided by Robert West Architects.</p><p> </p><p>The developer will be liable for the costs of any modification to the flood defences.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","106498 ; 106499 ; 107526","2017-10-19T11:45:45.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767490/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767490/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Flood Control: Greenwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Education Skills Funding Agency contacted his Department to discuss the cost and suitability of relocating flood defences on the Bowring Sports Ground before December 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","106497"
