 way for a free school on the Bowring Sports Ground; to who the cost of that work will fall; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","106498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767492","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Environment Agency has no record of any contact from the Education Skills Funding Agency prior to December 2015. The Environment Agency was contacted by the Education Skills Funding Agency in December 2015 regarding the potential purchase of land in Bowring Sports Ground to build a new school on the site.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency met the Education Skills Funding Agency in March 2016 to discuss their proposals and to provide planning advice. No change to the flood defences was proposed at that time. The proposal to relocate flood defences on the Bowring Sports Ground site was first put forward in June 2017 by Robert West Architects and discussions with them are ongoing.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Environment Agency requires developers to demonstrate that their proposals do not increase flood risk. The Environment Agency is a statutory consultee in the planning process. The Environment Agency will not support any application which does not include an adequate flood risk assessment. The Environment Agency will assess detailed proposals and a flood risk assessment in relation to this application, once provided by Robert West Architects.</p><p> </p><p>The developer will be liable for the costs of any modification to the flood defences.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","106497 ; 106498 ; 107526","2017-10-19T11:45:45.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767492/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767492/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Flood Control: Greenwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment has been made of the risk of flooding to properties adjacent to the Quaggy River as a consequence of relocating the flood defences on the Bowring Sports Ground site to make way for a free school; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","106499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767493","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-17","<p>We take the issue of illegal trafficking of puppies very seriously, and the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) are gathering intelligence to help us understand the size of the problem regarding puppy smuggling.</p><p>Defra and APHA work constructively with other government agencies and charities to share intelligence on illegal movements of pet animals. APHA has established an intelligence team which will gather data, intelligence and information on illegal movement of dogs and puppies and, as appropriate, share with enforcement bodies.</p><p>APHA works in partnership with the Dogs Trust and Kent County Council to identify and seize dogs and puppies which were not compliant with the requirements as part of a pilot project at Dover responding to intelligence on potential non-compliance. Approximately 600 puppies have been seized and taken into quarantine since the initiative began in December 2015.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-17T12:58:58.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767493/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767493/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Dogs: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the number of puppies being smuggled illegally into the UK.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767494","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-19","<ol><li><p>There are no plans to change the current legislation on colony cages for laying hens. However, we are preparing a new statutory laying hen code which will provide up to date guidance on how to comply with the legislation.</p><p> </p></li><li><p>We have made it very clear that we do not support the routine preventative use of antibiotics, or the use of antibiotics to compensate for poor animal husbandry. This is reflected in the revised “Responsible use of animal medicines on the farm” guidelines published in December 2014. We continue to work with the UK veterinary profession and livestock industry to:</p></li></ol><ul><li>develop and agree sector-specific reduction targets for antibiotic use;</li><li>support the development of prescribing and responsible use guidelines to encourage the adoption of best practice.</li></ul>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-19T15:31:38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767494/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767494/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Agriculture: Animal Welfare and Antibiotics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the (a) use of cage systems for farm animals and (b) routine preventative use of antibiotics in farms.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767495","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-25","<p>The draft North Sea Multi Annual Plan includes an upper range for fishing consistent with Maximum Sustainable Yield. Exploitation rates may be set within this upper range only in certain prescribed circumstances, for example to maintain balance in a mixed fishery. The UK supports this general approach, which we consider to be consistent with the principle of sustainable fisheries.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-25T09:57:28.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767495/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767495/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Fisheries: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will support the policy of the European Council of Ministers on the North Sea Multiannual Plan to legally sanction overfishing of bottom dwelling fish stocks such as cod and haddock over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","106530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767496","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>Where Maximum Sustainable Yield targets cannot be determined, due to lack of data, multiannual plans must provide for measures to be based on the precautionary approach. The Government’s view is that the precautionary approach should be strictly evidence-based, with such data-limited bycatch stocks managed on a case-by-case basis and in line with the plans’ objectives. For stocks with a presumption of stability we have supported maintaining TACs at current levels, unless scientific advice suggests otherwise. Where possible we support moving to a full analytical assessment that would enable TACs to be based on the MSY approach.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-18T17:33:58.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767496/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767496/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Fisheries: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 25 July 2017 to Question 5217, how the Government plans for bycatch fish species identified in the European Council of Ministers' General Approach to the North Sea Multi Annual Plan to be restored to and maintained above biomass levels capable of producing maximum sustainable yield in the event that fishing limits are not set in accordance with the Common Fisheries Policy objective to achieve the maximum sustainable yield exploitation rate by 2020 at the latest.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","106529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767497","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government set out an ambitious legislative programme in the Queen's speech in June. The timescales for forthcoming bills, including those on fisheries and agriculture, will be announced in the usual manner in due course.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-12T16:37:41.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767497/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767497/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Agriculture and Fisheries: Legislation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to bring forward the (a) agriculture and (b) fisheries bills which were announced in the 2017 Queen's Speech; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","106535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767498","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government remains committed to publishing a 25 year environment plan in due course.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-12T13:39:12.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767498/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767498/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Environment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when his Department plans to publish its 25 year environment plan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","106533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767499","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-13","<p>On 3 July the UK gave formal notification to withdraw from the London Fisheries Convention. The Convention has a 2 year notification period for withdrawal. The Secretary of State wrote to his counterparts in all Member States who have access to the UK’s 6-12 mile zone on 3 July.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-13T13:08:03.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767499/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767499/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Fisheries Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress his Department has made on withdrawal from the London Fisheries Convention; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","106534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767500","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>Defra is currently in the process of developing a new single animal activities licensing regime. The regulations will be laid in Parliament before they come into force next year. Pet shops and dog breeders will need to meet statutory minimum welfare standards which reflect the welfare requirements of the Animal Welfare Act 2006. Local authorities will need to have regard to supporting statutory guidance to help them apply the standards.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-18T17:38:41.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767500/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767500/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Pets: Shops","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans his Department has to introduce a standardised form of inspection for pet shops and dog breeders.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767501","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>Defra does not hold official statistics on the number of dog breeders and pet shops operating without a licence. Defra is currently in the process of developing a new single animal activities licensing regime. The regulations will be laid in Parliament before they come into force next year. The new regime will reduce the threshold by which people will need a dog breeding licence from five litters or more per year to three litters or more per year. This should result in more dog breeders requiring a licence. The new regime will make it clear for local authorities which individual activities need to be licensed.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","106512","2017-10-18T17:44:10.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767501/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767501/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Pets: Shops","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the prevalence of unlicensed (a) dog breeding and (b) pet shops in the UK.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","106736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767502","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-24","<p>Defra has supported a range of research relevant to improving understanding of the effects of neonicotinoids (and other pesticides) on bees. Recently completed work includes studies on: quantifying the exposure of bumblebees to neonicotinoids and mixtures of pesticides (commenced 2013), interpreting pesticide residues in honeybees (published 2015), using radio-frequency identification devices to assess effects of pesticides on foraging bees (commenced 2013), and protection goals for bee colonies (commenced 2015).</p><p> </p><p>The Government considers that decisions on the use of pesticides should be based on a careful scientific assessment of the risks. Pesticides that carry unacceptable risks to bees should not be authorised. The Government keeps the developing evidence on neonicotinoids under review, advised by the independent UK Expert Committee on Pesticides. On the basis of current available evidence, we support the existing restrictions.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-24T15:59:34.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767502/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767502/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Bees: Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of neonicotinoids on the native bee population.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","106809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767503","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-17","<p>We aim to consult on the third tranche of Marine Conservation Zones in English waters in the first half of 2018, with designations within 12 months of that date. The objective is to complete our contribution to the international ecologically coherent network of Marine Protected Areas in the North East Atlantic, by including a representative range of the species and habitats found in our seas.</p><p> </p><p>Marine protected areas in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are a devolved matter.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-17T15:03:36.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767503/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767503/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Marine Conservation Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has set a target date for the designation of an ecologically coherent network of maritime conservation zones.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","106814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767504","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Statutory Nature Conservation Bodies (Natural England and the Joint Nature Conservation Committee) provide assessments of Marine Protected Areas every 6 years. The next report is due next year. In addition to this, Inshore Fisheries and Conservation Authorities and the Marine Management Organisation are putting in place Monitoring Control Plans that measure the effectiveness of management measures in furthering the conservation objectives of Marine Protected Areas (MPAs).</p><p> </p><p>There are no “reference areas” designated.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-18T14:43:20.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767504/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767504/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Marine Conservation Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to (a) monitor and (b) measure the effect of maritime conservation zones on ecological recovery; and if such plans will include reference areas.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","106815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767505","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-12","<p>We aim to consult on the third tranche of Marine Conservation Zones in English waters in the first half of 2018, with designations within 12 months of that date.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-12T13:09:43.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767505/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767505/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Marine Conservation Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has plans to launch a consultation on tranche three of the marine conservation zone.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","106781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767506","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-12","<p>The European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Bill will ensure the whole body of existing EU environmental law continues to have effect in UK law, including the FLEGT regulation.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-12T16:42:08.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767506/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767506/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Forests: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to maintain Forest Law Enforcement Governance and Trade certification and market access to after UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","106780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767507","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>We continue to take action with the international community to press for improvements on all human rights issues in Iran, including prison conditions. We support the work of the Special Rapporteur for Human Rights in Iran. We regularly raise human rights with the Iranian government at all levels. I raised concerns about human rights, including prison conditions, with my Iranian counterpart during my visit to Iran on 5 August.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T15:36:42.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767507/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767507/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Iran: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations the Government has made to the Government of Iran on the treatment of (a) all political prisoners and (b) political prisoners on hunger strike at Gohardasht Prison.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767508","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>We encourage both Israel and the Palestinian Authority (PA) to take steps that rebuild trust and improve dialogue and communication which is crucial for negotiations to succeed. But whilst we and partners are doing all we can, ultimately peace will only come through fresh negotiations between the parties. The UK’s longstanding policy on reconciliation between the PA and Hamas is clear. We support the Palestinian people in realising self-determination through an independent, sovereign, and unified Palestinian state, in the West Bank and Gaza. We welcome Egyptian efforts to facilitate the return of the legitimate PA to Gaza, including enabling the recent PA Ministers’ visit to Gaza. We encourage those involved in the process to engage in good faith, allowing the PA to fully resume its government functions in Gaza, and ensuring compliance with the Quartet Principles.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T15:33:00.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767508/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767508/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to improve dialogue and communication between (a) Israel and Hamas, (b) Israel and the Palestinian Authority and (c) the Palestinian Authority and Hamas.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","106732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767509","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>There is an urgent need to address the troubling situation in Gaza. I visited Gaza on 21 August and saw the extent of this firsthand. Ultimately, Hamas' decision to embrace violence and reject the Quartet Principles lies at the heart of the Gazan tragedy. We need a durable agreement that addresses the underlying causes of the conflict and transforms the situation in Gaza.</p><p>We welcome the steps that Israel has taken to ease some restrictions. However, we want to see Israel go much further and we are continuing to call on Israel to do so. We continue to stress to the Israeli authorities the damage that their restrictions are doing to the living standards of ordinary Palestinians in Gaza and that supporting legal trade for Gazans is firmly in Israel's long-term interests.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T15:31:02.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767509/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767509/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Gaza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to end the blockade of the Gaza strip by Israel.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","106731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767510","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Prime Minister, the Foreign Secretary and I raised a number of bilateral issues, including all our dual-national consular cases, with our Iranian counterparts in the margins of the United Nations General Assembly in September. Iran’s position on dual nationality makes progress on our consular cases difficult; nonetheless we continue to raise these cases with the Iranian authorities at the highest levels and at every available opportunity. We assess that the approach we currently take is the one that is the most likely to be in the best interests of each of our dual-national prisoners in Iran.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T15:29:01.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767510/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767510/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Iran: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he had with his Iranian counterparts at the recent UN General Assembly in New York (a) in general and (b) on detained British-Iranian dual nationals.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767511","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>We are urgently seeking clarification from the Iranian authorities on reports that Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe is subject to further charges. I called the Iranian Ambassador to express my concerns, as did the Foreign Secretary in a call to Foreign Minister Zarif and a meeting with Vice-President Salehi on 11 October, but the scope of any additional charges remains unclear. Our Ambassador is continuing to press the Iranian authorities for further information.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T15:21:59.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767511/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767511/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Iranian Government about the new charges being brought against Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe,","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","106656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767512","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>There have been no recent discussions between the Foreign Secretary and his Chinese counterpart on retaining animal habitats in and around China. However our Embassy in Beijing is in regular discussions with the Chinese Government and local organisations regarding environmental issues and the Illegal Wildlife Trade.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-17T15:48:11.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767512/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767512/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","China: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to China on retaining habitats for animals on land in the seas around that country and in forests.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767513","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The British Government opposes the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and takes any allegations of extrajudicial killings seriously. Whilst at present we have no plans to request an inquiry by the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights, we continue to take action with the international community to press for improvements on all human rights issues in Iran, including ending the death penalty and by supporting the work done by the Special Rapporteur for Human Rights in Iran. We also raise our concerns directly with the Iranian government and I was able to raise this directly with my Iranian counterpart during my visit to Tehran in August this year.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T15:38:47.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767513/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767513/answer",,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-09","Iran: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will request that the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights investigates the 1988 executions of political prisoners in Iran.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106808"
