"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767552","Department of Health","false","2017-10-17","<p>Following a detailed public consultation that ran from December 2015 to March 2016, the Government set out in its response to that consultation in February 2017 that it intended to amend the existing Charging Regulations. The Government also set out in the response its intention to require up-front charging in respect of non-urgent treatment. This commitment did not constitute a change in policy since existing published guidance has always stated that National Health Service providers should identify and charge patients not eligible for free NHS care upfront, for any care deemed not urgent or immediately necessary by a clinician. Both before and after the consultation response was published, the Department’s Overseas Visitor and Migrant NHS Cost Recovery Programme has been working extensively with the frontline to support adherence to the guidance.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-17T15:45:36.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767552/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767552/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what consultation his Department undertook before introducing up-front charging for the NHS care of non-British citizens.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767553","Department of Health","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-17T15:42:52.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767553/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767553/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Hospitals: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of hospitals which have had a leak to the roof in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767554","Department of Health","false","2017-10-17","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has recommended that Immediate Release (IR) Fentanyl should not be offered as a first-line fast acting pain relief and NHS England’s clinical working group considered that the current high prescribing volumes were not justified given the small number of patients for whom IR fentanyl would be appropriate, namely those suffering from cancer.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The clinical working group considered therefore that more cost effective products were available for those patients being prescribed the drug who were not cancer patients. Their guidance does not class IR Fentanyl as a low priority for funding. It clarifies the circumstances in which it should be prescribed.</p><p> </p><p>However, where there is an absence of final guidance recommendations from NICE, decisions on the funding of a licensed treatment on the National Health Service are taken by the relevant clinician and commissioner (such as NHS England or individual clinical commissioning groups) based on the individual needs of the patient.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-17T16:37:41.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767554/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767554/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Fentanyl","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons fentanyl has been classified as a low priority for funding.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767555","Department of Health","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally. It is for individual National Health Service hospitals to make their own arrangements to deal with, or otherwise ensure the prevention of, pest infestations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-17T15:44:28.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767555/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767555/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Hospitals: Pest Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospitals reported infestations of rats and mice in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767556","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>Nene and Corby Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs) advise that they continue to work closely with partners and stakeholders to ensure that the urgent care services provided to the people of North Northamptonshire are responsive and fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p>As part of this work, the local National Health Service is developing an integrated emergency care specification in line with the national policy direction and will continue, through the Northamptonshire Sustainability and Transformation Plan, to ensure quality urgent care services in Northamptonshire.</p><p> </p><p>We understand that Kettering General Hospital NHS Foundation Trust is developing an Outline Business Case for an Urgent Care Hub, and that NHS Improvement is engaging with the Trust on this.</p><p> </p><p>An agreement has been reached between NHS Corby CCG and Lakeside+ Limited to extend the contract to run Corby Urgent Care Centre. The contract will be subject to an extension from 1 October 2017 that will allow it to continue up to but not beyond 31 March 2019.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-12T14:36:33.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767556/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767556/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Urgent Treatment Centres: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on improving urgent care centres in North Northamptonshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","106540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767557","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government understand the pressures that general practitioners (GPs) face and regularly discusses issues related to general practice with the British Medical Association.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working to increase capacity in general practice. The General Practice Forward View set out plans for an extra 5,000 doctors working in general practice by 2020, as well as a minimum of 5,000 other staff – including mental health therapists, practice nurses and clinical pharmacists. In addition, a number of initiatives have been launched to help reduce practice workload and free up time for GPs to provide care to their patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-12T13:09:49.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767557/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767557/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has made an assessment of the implications for his policies of the proportion of GP practices that responded to a BMA survey stating that they would consider temporarily suspending new patient registration in order to focus on delivering safe care to patients already on their practice lists.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","106532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767558","Department of Health","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. The Department collects data from National Health Service trusts for the average total daily cost for the provision of all meals and beverages fed to one patient per day; not the cost of a single meal.</p><p> </p><p>The average cost of feeding one in-patient per day is £11.05. The cost is inclusive of all pay and non-pay costs, including provisions, ward issues, disposables, equipment and its maintenance.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-17T15:54:20.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767558/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767558/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Hospitals: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average cost is of preparing and serving a meal in NHS hospitals.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767559","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>Mandatory nutrition labelling, including the display of calories, for the majority of pre-packaged foods came into effect in December 2016 and is harmonised by European Union legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The United Kingdom’s decision to leave the EU may give us an opportunity to develop greater flexibility, as the exit terms are agreed, to determine what information should be presented and how it should be displayed in the UK.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-12T13:14:42.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767559/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767559/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Food: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the research basis is for the decision his Department has taken not to make calorie labelling mandatory.","false","Biography information for Bambos Charalambous","Enfield, Southgate","Bambos Charalambous","106504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767560","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>‘Stepping forward to 2020/21: The mental health workforce plan for England’ was published in July. This sets out steps for recruiting and retaining 21,000 new staff across the mental health system, with the expectation that 19,000 of these places would be filled by staff employed directly by the National Health Service. The plan includes tangible steps to increase the numbers of junior doctors choosing psychiatry.</p><p> </p><p>The plan can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.hee.nhs.uk/our-work/person-centred-care/mental-health/mental-health-workforce-plan" target="_blank">https://www.hee.nhs.uk/our-work/person-centred-care/mental-health/mental-health-workforce-plan</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-10-12T13:38:50.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767560/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767560/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Psychiatry: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure the training of more child psychiatrists; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","106505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767561","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>DFID supports the achievement of the global malaria targets for 2030; these include aiming for at least a 90% reduction of malaria deaths from a 2015 baseline. The World Health Organisation estimates that this will require the total annual malaria spend to reach an estimated US$ 8.7 billion by 2030. DFID is the second largest international funder to the global malaria response.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T17:06:49.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767561/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767561/answer",,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Malaria: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate her Department has made of the international financing required to end malaria.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767562","Department of Health","false","2017-10-13","<p>No such discussions have taken place. It is for content makers to decide what to include in their programmes, provided that they comply with the Broadcasting Code. As television reflects real life, it can be expected that some people on television may smoke and drink alcohol. In respect of children and young people, the Ofcom Broadcasting Code stipulates that smoking, drugs and the misuse of alcohol must not be featured in programmes made primarily for children, and must generally be avoided and not condoned, encouraged, or glamorised before the watershed or in programmes likely to be seen by children.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-13T13:36:16.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767562/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767562/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-09","Alcoholic Drinks and Smoking: Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with television companies on reducing the prevalence of smoking and alcohol consumption in programming.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106803"
